- `j` is the index in `partialSums` where we first find a value greater than `i`, minus 1
- `k = i - (take j L).flatten.length`

The key insight is that `partialSums` gives us cumulative sums, so:
- `(L.map length).partialSums[j]` is the total length of the first `j` sublists
- `(L.map length).partialSums[j+1]` is the total length of the first `j+1` sublists
- Since `j+1` is the first index where the partial sum exceeds `i`, we have `partialSums[j] ≤ i < partialSums[j+1]`

This means `i - partialSums[j] < L[j].length`.

